UPDATE designers SET biography = E'Pierre Yovanovitch grew up in Nice, France, to an industrialist Yugoslavian father and a French mother. He would later credit the fact that he grew up with very few family heirlooms as inspiration for creating his own legacy. After attending business school in Paris, he met Pierre Cardin, who offered him an apprenticeship. He worked for Cardin for eight years — first as a menswear license manager, then as a designer for his menswear collections — developing a passion for shape, form, and what he calls Cardin\'s quality as an "architect of clothing."\n\nAfter leaving Cardin, Yovanovitch launched his interior design practice, transforming his first Parisian apartment over two decades ago. From the early days of his practice, he drew inspiration from the Swedish Grace movement — particularly Axel Einar Hjorth and Gunnar Asplund — as well as early 20th-century American designers including Paul László, T.H. Robsjohn-Gibbings, and Harvey Probber. He also cites Jean-Michel Frank, Pierre Chareau, and Jean Royère among his long-standing influences.\n\nhttps://www.nowness.com/iframe?id=6076837351001&subtitles=en | Pierre Yovanovitch for NOWNESS |\n\nIn 2021, Pierre Yovanovitch Mobilier was established, combining his made-to-measure approach with craftsmanship, materiality, and sustainable sourcing. The brand works with artisans in France and Switzerland who utilise traditional crafting techniques, focusing on locally and sustainably sourced wood, natural fibres, hand-blown glass, and organic, non-toxic adhesives.\n\nhttps://res.cloudinary.com/dif1oamtj/image/upload/v1774943859/Screen_Shot_2026-03-31_at_3.57.22_PM_q3xeen.png | | left\n\nHis own home, Château de Fabrègues in Provence — constructed in the early 17th century — serves as a platform for his creative expression, featuring site-specific contemporary art commissions by artists such as Claire Tabouret, Tadashi Kawamata, and Daniel Buren.\n\nhttps://res.cloudinary.com/dif1oamtj/image/upload/v1774943936/Screen_Shot_2026-03-31_at_3.58.37_PM_gkitkn.png | | right\n\nYovanovitch\'s interiors are defined by a sculptural sensitivity — an ability to balance monumental gestures with intimate warmth. His spaces are characterised by curved forms, restrained palettes, and a reverence for natural light.\n\nhttps://res.cloudinary.com/dif1oamtj/image/upload/v1774944038/Screen_Shot_2026-03-31_at_3.59.43_PM_mjcdyf.png | | left\n\nEach project reflects a deep dialogue between architecture, art, and craft — a philosophy that has earned him a reputation as one of the most distinctive voices in contemporary European design.', updated_at = now() WHERE slug = 'pierre-yovanovitch';